column14:
Webchat - improves access and choice of access particularly for BAME, deaf and autistic groups

Natural Language / Alex a type call queuing system - available in multi language to attract and support BAME communities

Outbound campaigns - as above

&nbsp;

The above will expedite us when also involved in track trace call handling

&nbsp;

column7:
Open Banking (OB) was originally designed for use in the lending sector. Investigations have determined that the functionality is available for utilising the same information for local taxation income/expenditure assessments.

&nbsp;

OB data has been analysed and converted to produce an income/expenditure report which aligns with the Standard Financial Statement (SFS) developed by the Money and Pensions Service. Data has been cross referenced and matched to the categories used in the SFS with detailed reports having been developed.

&nbsp;

This means that taxpayers can provide verified, accurate and complete information for the assessment of arrangements, ensuring that the offers are sustainable for customers and suitable to the Council in terms of reaching an agreed solution to ongoing indebtedness. Investigations have found that this functionality is currently available.

&nbsp;

The second phase is to automate the application/assessment process to scale up the opportunity to deal with the large volume of local taxpayers who have fallen into arrears as a result of the recent pandemic whilst reducing the need for face to face contact and it is this stage which requires funding.

&nbsp;

Although initial investigations have identified the functionality is available on the market. Walsall would undergo a procurement process to ensure fairness and openness

column13:
Once developed, this project will be transferrable to any other interested authority. The proposed project will be designed in a way that any authority will be able to take advantage of the development without duplicating the development costs associated with such an innovation.

&nbsp;

Access to OB requires subscription and transaction costs by any Council wishing to use it. To date, the Council is not aware of any other billing authority using this functionality and so development work is required to apply it to this field. By funding the project, it means that other Councils can subscribe to the service at a significantly reduced cost, because development costs will have been incorporated into this project.

&nbsp;

Walsall Council will operate as a beta site and also provide a case study, including cost benefit analysis on an open book basis to assist other Councils to build a business case for its use.

column14:
The project specifically relates to Open Banking. It therefore necessarily requires customers to have online access to their bank accounts. ONS data states that 75% of the UK population use online banking regularly, the majority of which are of working age, which aligns well with local taxation liability.

&nbsp;

However, the Council understands that some customers are digitally excluded. Therefore, in concert with this project, the Council will continue to operate existing processes enabling digitally excluded segments of the population to receive the same level of service. Since one of the main outcomes to this project is more resource efficient operations for the Council, it means that existing staffing resources can be more effectively allocated to those customers that require a more individual service to achieve the desired outcome.

&nbsp;

The service will be accessible through the Council’s website, which is designed in line with GDS (Government Digital Service) standards for accessibility.

column17:
Although initial investigations have identified the functionality is available on the market. Walsall would undergo a procurement process to ensure fairness and openness. It is necessary to use external partners as open banking is regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and European equivalents and only regulated providers can supply the information.

&nbsp;

Since the Money and Pensions Service is keen to encourage use of the SFS by Councils, it would be helpful to liaise with them to ensure the automation aligns with their objectives and to assist in promoting this project to other interested Councils.

column7:
This work builds on work undertaken 2 years ago looking at long-term causes of homelessness – family, personal and institutional factors. Recognition of these triggers changed the way we delivered services, seeking to mitigate risk rather than wait for need.

&nbsp;

Since then academic research including the <a href="https://www.stress.org/holmes-rahe-stress-inventory">Holmes-Rahe Stress score</a>, work on adverse childhood events, and wider determinants of health informed a scoring system to weight the consolidated risk of life events in both childhood and adulthood. This has been used to start to calibrate the point at which accumulated risk becomes unsustainable, through mapping risk retrospectively onto the life stories of residents who ended up in crisis.

&nbsp;

During Covid, HDC deployed a <a href="https://www.wearehuntingdonshire.org/">digital approach</a> and used a simplified set of data to undertake risk-based outbound contact and speak to 8,796 households. Not offering a service but providing welfare checks and signposting available solutions or solutions of resilience support e.g. befriending services.

&nbsp;

Some impacts of Covid (job and income loss, bereavement, isolation) create immediate need but are also known risk factors for other poor long-term outcomes. A number of authorities have come together to test this approach through <a href="https://www.nesta.org.uk/project-updates/measurement-learning-methods-tools-to-enable-improvement/">collaborative work</a> with NESTA and CPI. This is the basis of this next phase.

column13:
At the end of the process a peer reviewed holistic risk index for key underlying risk will exist, alongside a calibrated underlying risk trigger score (e.g. when does risk become crisis) for people who have experienced crisis in a number of different geographical and structural settings. There is little in this space that does not work thematically e.g. education, social care, ASC client. The impact of this is unmanaged risk moving between agencies e.g. care leaver to housing services, and a lack of holistic focus on the foundations of a resilient life e.g. sustainable income, housing, social bonds.

&nbsp;

Using Gov.notiify and Power Apps will mean integrations will be as widely reusable as possible and leverage previous investment, and industry standard tools.

&nbsp;

The impact of proactive preventative outbound comms, would be applicable even in instances in which other agencies would not do this on the basis of sophisticated risk profiling.

column7:
Scoping work has been undertaken to determine whether the proposed solution is fit for purpose. Officers have engaged with colleagues from a range of public sector and private sector organisations to establish learning and best practice and applied this to the Knowsley’s requirements.

&nbsp;

Officers have met on site with two private sector partners with established track records and who have indicated an ability to implement and deliver a programme within timescales which meets identified need.

&nbsp;

Officers have also consulted with equality and diversity leads to ensure that the needs of all residents are identified and supported wherever possible.

&nbsp;

Utilising this, Officers have developed a specification which has been published on the Council’s “Chest” in accordance with Council Financial Procedure Rules for tender. This will enable the Council to determine whether the solution is financially viable but also ensure that the Council is able to meet the deadlines prescribed by this grant.

&nbsp;

NOTE: SPECIFICATION AVAILABLE

column8:
During COVID the Council has made huge steps forward to increase accessibility to its public meetings, it is recognised that this has increased community engagement and this project is intended to build on learning by implementing a permanent solution which will support this moving forward.

&nbsp;

<u>Stage 1: Scoping and Understanding Need - COMPLETED</u>

&nbsp;

Officers have engaged with a range of public sector (nationally) and private sector partners to understand technological availability and to identify what has worked well and what could be enhanced. This has been utilised to develop a tender specification.

&nbsp;

<u>Stage 2: Tender Exercise – ONGOING</u>

&nbsp;

A specification has been published on the Council’s “Chest” in accordance with procurement rules. Named private sector partners with expertise and a track record for delivery of these programmes have been invited to bid. The deadline for submission is noon on Monday 13 July 2020. The tenders will then be subject to evaluation. Progression of the project will be dependent upon cost and grant funding. The tender process has ensured that contractors are on standby and able to progress with the project should the grant application be successful.

&nbsp;

<u>Stage 3: Contract Tender and Delivery - PENDING</u>

&nbsp;

Contractors have indicated that there would be a maximum six week lead in period and a subsequent 2 week installation period.

&nbsp;

Private Sector Partners – The tender is currently open for public sector partners to bid. This is a requirement of the Council’s procurement processes. Tenders will be evaluated before a preferred partner can be identified. All of this has been done to ensure that the programme can be delivered within the timescales prescribed.

&nbsp;

Resources – The Council has ensured that IT and Officer support is available to deliver this programme.

&nbsp;

Engagement – Enhanced public engagement throughout COVID has been positive, this project would look to enhance and continue this.

column13:
The ability to hold the Council’s meetings remotely on site (whether or not in hybrid fashion) will support the Council’s input and interaction with other authorities within the area. Knowsley Council is one of the constituent authorities forming the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority.  Our experiences of this solution including the success factors mentioned in 5.5 above will be shared with our City Region and other peers to promote improvements in the democratic process across the country.

&nbsp;

Learning and use is not limited solely to the democratic process, but instead this technology can also be utilised to enhance engagement with residents of public/private sector partners when not being utilised for meetings. This learning can and will continue to be shared with all partners to ensure best practice and learning nationally.

column14:
The introduction of the new system will mean that members of the public would no longer have to attend the Council buildings (in the future) in order to engage in democratic or consultation processes but would instead be able to access meetings from the comfort of their own homes or workplace. For those without access to hardware, access will be available via one of the Council’s facilities in their locality, e.g. libraries and One Stop Shops.  In the future, this option will be available in addition to the ability to attend on site.

&nbsp;

The Council has a proven track record of supporting its community in the take up of digital services with online transactions increasing from just 3% to 75% in a period of 3 years. A key element of this success was engaging with residents and businesses to support them and make them digital aware and competent as required.

column17:
The Council works with other authorities within the City Region on a partnership.  Work will be undertaken with colleagues across the Region to support engagement by Elected Members and members of the public in the democratic process and consultation with the recovery phase.

&nbsp;

Learning will be available to public sector partners to support this approach being used to enhance community engagement with local decision making, eg. the Council hosts the Police and Crime Panel Meetings and works with Police and Fire Colleagues in ASB and Crime Hotspots, technology could support these approaches which would add value to the proposal.

column7:
We are enthusiastic about the opportunity of combining the geodata expertise of Westminster and Camden with the expertise that can be provided by Urban Intelligence (UI) <a href="https://w3.urbanintelligence.co.uk/index.html">https://w3.urbanintelligence.co.uk/index.html</a> to explore further, new methods for understanding the impact of rapidly changing consumer behaviour on the retail and service uses within our boroughs, particularly given the current acceleration of these changes due to the impacts of COVID-19. The project will be ‘starting from scratch’, but will utilise the variety of experience that UI has developed in using urban data analytics over recent years. The key differentiator is the ability to create or use data sets and a methodology that creates a dynamic evidence base, capable of easier update in future and therefore greater ease of comparison. The Councils will make available previous retail studies and more recent market update surveys prior to the project start date to speed up UI’s initial understanding of what we already know about the commercial centres within our boroughs.

&nbsp;

Much of Westminster’s and Camden’s existing evidence base is available online;

<a href="https://www.westminster.gov.uk/economic-growth-and-development">https://www.westminster.gov.uk/economic-growth-and-development</a>

<a href="https://www.westminster.gov.uk/cityplan2040">https://www.westminster.gov.uk/cityplan2040</a>

&nbsp;

<a href="https://opendata.camden.gov.uk/Planning/Camden-Retail-Frontages-Survey/2j3j-7nbw">https://opendata.camden.gov.uk/Planning/Camden-Retail-Frontages-Survey/2j3j-7nbw</a>

<a href="https://www.camden.gov.uk/evidence-and-supporting-documents?inheritRedirect=true">https://www.camden.gov.uk/evidence-and-supporting-documents?inheritRedirect=true</a>

In order to share data to enable joint working during lockdown, a number of emergency data sharing arrangements have been put in place which rely on manual processes to collate, share and cross reference data.

&nbsp;

This means that we have a basic understanding of the data that partners require from others, the systems that are in use and there are a number of manual processes we can build on.

&nbsp;

A number of additional software solutions have been identified that could provide the require data sharing solution, these are Patient Knows Best, E-CINS and RISE by Housing Partners.

&nbsp;

Patient Knows Best and E-CINS are already available for us to use at no additional cost. RISE is a new module that will be ready to use in August that has been demonstrated to us. We have an opportunity to become an early adopter of the module and influence the final configuration of the module. Housing Partners have also confirmed that it can connect to other systems through APIs, though this may require development time and budget.

column13:
The out puts of the project will be useable by all 7 district/borough authorities in Nottinghamshire, as well as Nottinghamshire County Council and Nottingham and Nottinghamshire Clinical Commissioning Group.

&nbsp;

Both the data sharing requirements and the systems used by partners and those to be considered in this project are widely used throughout the country by organisations working with individuals rough sleeping and so the findings of the scoping exercise, the pilot and the recommendations of an effective data sharing solution will be applicable to a large number of other authorities who would be able to use these outputs as the starting point for their own projects.

column10:
This award would enable the further development of an integrated monitoring and surveillance tool analysis market changes, operational threats, risks, and provider resilience to support joined-up decision making and drive health and social care system-wide working to its potential.

&nbsp;

The final product will be a cross-system resource exploring trends and providing bench marked comparisons for care home providers across areas, providers, sectors and subsectors as well as meaningful, actionable insights at individual care home level.

&nbsp;

Success and impact from the project will be demonstrated through the delivery of the final dashboards for providers across the health and social care system. These tools will be used across local partners to share information and intelligence quickly and effectively.

&nbsp;

We will hold a review session two months post launch of the new dashboards to review progress and ascertain impact and success achieved. This review will look at the extent to which this product has been used by different partners across the Health and Social Care sector as well as featuring case studies demonstrating the impact. The focus will include identifying innovative ways of commissioning and delivering health and care not just confined to individual organisations’ contractual goals but across the wider local market.

column7:
The Council’s Workforce Cell and Resource Hub have developed a ‘Future Reservist Model’ which sets out the purpose of what we are aiming to achieve (see Appendix 1). This builds upon work that we have already done to date during this pandemic, which has served as a pilot for this model. This model has now been endorsed by our Extended Management Team.

&nbsp;

In order to operate this model we need the digital infrastructure (developments to existing systems) to support this, building upon manual systems that we have been using to date. A project plan has been developed to outline the work needed to achieve this (see Appendix 2).

column8:
Our project plan in Appendix 2 sets out the key dates within which different elements of the plan will be achieved. We are unable to be more specific about actual dates within the 8-week window outlined until we have confirmation of funding and have secured agreed consultancy dates.

&nbsp;

As can be seen, we will be ready to commence the work on 3 August 2020 and planning has already commenced in preparation for this.

&nbsp;

Other considerations:

&nbsp;

<strong>Resources</strong>

<strong> </strong>

We have internal expertise within our HR Systems Team who will be able to deliver elements of this work. We would have hoped to bring in additional resource but is not likely to be achievable within the 8 week window and proposed commencement date and so overtime (at a rate of time and a third) will need to be provided. This, added with to consultancy support from our software provider (MHR), will ensure that the project is deliverable.

&nbsp;

<strong>Involvement from the Local Government Sector</strong>

&nbsp;

No additional involvement required, although intelligence gathered via the GM Collaboration around approaches to the deployment of staff during the pandemic will feed into our approach.

&nbsp;

<strong>Data Requirements</strong>

<strong> </strong>

We have already mapped out the data requirements of this project, which have fed into the project plan. Manual systems were established to enable us to the data we have needed to data to effectively deploy staff, and we look to improve and develop this further as part of this project.

&nbsp;

<strong>Involvement from the broader population</strong>

<strong> </strong>

None required.

column13:
We have developed a ‘Reservist Model’ that we believe could be replicated within other Councils. The model can be showcased as good practice as a means of providing an effective framework through which to build and develop a flexible workforce which will support civil contingencies, business continuity and emergency planning responses.

&nbsp;

The ability to develop and adapt our HR &amp; Payroll System to provide the digital infrastructure to capture relevant data, monitor the movement of staff, and enable us to report on and understand how our workforce is being ‘flexed’ and ‘deployed’ at any time to meet the needs of our critical services is something that can be easily be shared.

&nbsp;

Certainly many of the local authorities across GM (and beyond) utilise the MHR ITrent System, and we are part of collaborative groups that share good practice and learning so can help advise others regarding how to achieve similar outcomes.

column14:
Our MHR ITrent HR &amp; Payroll System is accessible to our whole workforce (both on and off network) which includes our remote workforce who have no access to IT as part of their job role.

&nbsp;

We have both Manager and Employee self-service which does have an accessible view. Once enabled we are advised that the screens meet the WCAG 2.0 Level AA standards.

&nbsp;

Other functionality to assist with accessibility includes - ability to change shipped background colours and texts to match AA accessibility standards with regards to colour contrast, ability to resize up to 200% zoom, automatic display of help test when focusing onto a field etc

column8:
We are about to prototype the form, but limited time, capacity and expertise means that is relatively crude, particularly in appearance.  The project would see the user interfaced replaced by moving imagery, either human or avatar, more fully illustrating workplace requirements, with a simple yes/no, pass/fail option for the user.

The project would require specialist graphic expertise which is should overlay the SQL database.

&nbsp;

column7:
Maybe* has deployed its platform across the UK and can already demonstrate the ability to access specific information for the Rochford area.  Maybe* are a consortium partner of the High Street Task Force and their platform provides stakeholders with a dashboard that consolidates all local digital business activity across the key social media platforms.

&nbsp;

The technology is demonstrated with current data revealing who is active on social media and which businesses are getting positive results.

&nbsp;

This is not just another app!  Maybe*’s comprehensive implementation programme will enable us to showcase and promote the concept of “place”; engaging both businesses and consumers in our efforts to reimagine and drive success of our High Streets.

column13:
The platform that has been selected is scalable to any other UK council. It's already gathering the insights from Google Maps, Facebook, Twitter, Instagram across 1.5m UK high street business across 3,300 locations.

&nbsp;

We are happy to share our findings form the pilot

column8:
The key dates below outline the timeline to technical beta of a prototype build:

&nbsp;

Key dates and milestones –

&nbsp;

Week 1 – 2-  analysis of existing potential data sources.  Discussions around GDPR implications of sharing user data across multiple systems and partners.

Week 2 - data requirements reviewed.

Week 3- 8 data cleansing of required data for proof of concept (POC) development and analysis of this process to gather data on scalability and identification of issues.

Week 3 &amp; ongoing- development of POC prototype with ongoing engagement with partners for feedback and conversations regarding methods of access.

Week 7- data pulled into prototype for beta launch with partnership organisations.

Week 8- feedback and analysis and drafting of lessons learnt report.

&nbsp;

As outlined above we have an engaged cross-sector project team who have capacity to move the project forward quickly.

&nbsp;

Due to this engagement, and the work which has been undertaken for previous emergencies we already have access to a significant amount of data which could be used to establish the POC solution and processes.

&nbsp;

Users will include LRF partners with whom the data will be shared.  There will be involvement from across local government organisations within Cumbria, as well as Lancashire and Dumfries and Galloway Council where crossover occurs for emergency planning activities.  We are also keen to work with other two tier areas around sharing of data across county and district authorities.

&nbsp;

It is not anticipated in the first phase that the public will have access to the solution.  However early discussions have highlighted that a potential future phase could include some integration with ‘My account’ functionality at County or District level to allow the public to ensure that key information and contact details are kept up-to-date.

column13:
Partners from Gateshead Council will be involved in this project, to maximise the potential for relevant output technologies, resources or working practices to be translated to their care services.

&nbsp;

This is also intended to enable the benefits of this project to be distributed across the region and reduce the disruption faced by service users when they move between the neighbouring local authority areas.

Learning from the project will be shared online via blog posts, videos and presentations.

&nbsp;

NCC’s adult social care team is already part of a UK-wide network of council’s that are exploring the use of digital technologies in care provision.

&nbsp;

Communication materials on the methodology, findings and success of the discovery phase and alpha testing will be made available to the team for sharing among this community.

column14:
This project will explicitly consider the potential to widen digital participation and to demonstrate the impact of digital participation on health.

&nbsp;

Personal care plans will actively include measures to overcome barriers to digital participation, such as providing links to organisations providing digital inclusion support. This recognises that digital knowledge and skills will greatly impact the confidence a person has in managing their own health.

&nbsp;

The project will also build knowledge and confidence in using digital technologies amongst care workers. This will make it more likely that they recommend digital tools to their patients and will help to overcome a significant barrier to digital inclusion.

column13:
The system is used across England by several local authorities in managing their response to the Covid19 crisis. Any resulting improvements in the system would be available to all users where operating models were identical. Where there were similarities in operating models, councils would be able to reconfigure the system   more quickly and with less interruption, thereby increasing efficiencies and minimising disruption to front-line services.

The enhanced data &amp; reporting model created by the system supplier would be available to all other councils who use the product, thereby creating a consistent, benchmarkable, evidence-base helping organisations increase their understanding of the scale of local issues and to design their responses to these issues in an intelligence-led, proportionate, manner. It will also help facilitate data sharing through to Office of Data Analytics programmes developing within Local Authorities across the country.

&nbsp;

column7:
The Council has built its own volunteer database in response to COVID-19 which has worked well but stands in isolation of the wider community offer. The Council is keen to build on this, and as part of its COVID 19 response has become aware of best in class platforms.

&nbsp;

One of the solutions was a software company called TeamKinetic. The company gave a demonstration of the software and how it works to the project team below and we believe this platform would enable the Council to work with our voluntary sector partners to develop one universal database and would enable increase community engagement in line with our Knowsley Better Together principles - particularly working with others co-operatively across the community when making decisions.

&nbsp;

TeamKinetic has been built on the principles of Open Data and has developed an extensive publicly available API for the sharing and linking of volunteer and opportunity data across the partners of the Liverpool City Region.

&nbsp;

TeamKinetic has a proven track record of delivering similar multi-stakeholder solutions with Manchester City Council (12,000 volunteers) and Glasgow City Council (6000 volunteers) that has brought together local government, 3<sup>rd</sup> sector, NHS and other elements such as major events and sports.

column13:
Good networks and relationships are well established within the Liverpool City Region (LCR). Some of the voluntary sectors organisations in the region use this software but in the longer term the vision would be to develop a LCR approach to volunteering with a common platform for all partners.

&nbsp;

Learnings will be shared across the Liverpool City Region, the Volunteering and Shielded Cell for Merseyside Resilience Forum, and the VS6 (partnership of support organisations working with the 8,600 voluntary, community, faith and social enterprise (VCFSE) groups operating across our Liverpool City Region (LCR).

&nbsp;

TeamKinetic is provided as a SaaS solution, but improvements and developments in deployment made to the product as a result of this project will benefit all TeamKinetic customers which already includes councils from across the UK

column14:
TeamKinetic work with partners from the Glasgow Disability Partnership, Durham and Manchester City Council Accessibility Team and British Blind Sport to ensure we are always working to the very highest standards of accessibility and our site comfortably archives WCAG 2.1 level AA as set by <a href="https://www.w3.org/">The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C)</a>.

&nbsp;

TeamKinetic is a digital first product but is also accessible to users who may not be digitally engaged using our ‘managed user features’. This allows people who require additional support the ability to have an account set up and managed on their behalf and takes advantage of technology such as SMS texts and telephone to keep the individual engaged.

column17:
The Council works closely with its Communities and initially it is planned to develop a joint volunteer platform with One Knowsley and its community partners.

&nbsp;

Work will be undertaken collaboratively with colleagues across the City Region (as detailed in our response to 6.1) with a view to developing a wider volunteer network through Team Kinetic.

&nbsp;

This deployment of the platform will also create a good basis to recruit new volunteers as Knowsley is set to be the LCR Borough of Culture in 2022 when the Shakespeare North Playhouse opens.

column13:
This project will contain a work package to create a guide for local authorities for using business data. It will record and document the lessons learned and benefits created from linking public and private data sets to generate new insights to inform decisions making for the Build and Recover plan and wider local and regional government economic development objectives.

&nbsp;

The lessons learned document will also publish the methodology developed to generate the insights and user research so other public bodies can replicate the work with providers in their local areas. WLA will work with LOTI and MHCLG Teams to run 2 x borough workshops on business data to ensure the findings are disseminated and the value created by this project is captured and transferred to all local authority economic development teams.

column14:
The insights and intelligence generated by this project will allow the West London boroughs to develop new working practices that will accelerate growth in key sectors and ensure our residents and young people can benefit.

&nbsp;

It will provide essential information on local labour demands to inform Further Education colleges, careers services, and young people on opportunities with local businesses. It will support the West London Skill and Employment Board target programmes to the areas that will the greatest economic impact. By deploying resources to develop the skills needed to boost productivity and create jobs

column8:
Working in partnership with NPS, Snook and Policy in Practice (PiP), we will build on our existing pilot to focus on proactive identification of families, taking the pilot to the next level as previously we focused only on those applying for hardship grants.

&nbsp;

We will develop a service that is user-centred, increases citizen engagement but is cost-effective and efficient, enabling LA’s to invest in this approach and see return on investment through increased income and cost savings.

&nbsp;

Snook will develop and refine the service, building on the work conducted to date by NPS, taking a user-centred design approach.

&nbsp;

Through user-research with families and council officials they will develop a replicable service model that can be shared openly with LA’s and test the functionality of the software with PiP to support development of improvements.

We are committed to continuing the development of this work and learning from the pilot programme on how to refine and target maximization of benefits. We are also actively developing new ways to connect with people within the social distancing regulations.

&nbsp;

We will connect with the broader population through interviews, those who have accessed the service and those who are eligible.

&nbsp;

<strong>Delivery and Key Milestones:</strong>

&nbsp;

Week-1: kick-off, develop hypotheses, familiarisation with context and software.

Week-2/3: research sprints with citizens, officers and members of the council, third-sector and advocacy groups

Week-4: analysis and synthesis of research and development of service and product concepts

<strong>Milestone </strong>– research report and outline service propositions to be tested

Week-5/6: testing of communication methods, service propositions and technical development of product

Week-7/8: prototyping and testing with specific users to measure impact and evidence scalable impact

<strong>Milestone</strong> – production of report, giving outline of service model, benefits achieved to date and potential benefits to citizens and local authorities

column13:
Our website and social media communications (across all major platforms) will be enhanced by short video case studies that capture the main learning points from the project.

&nbsp;

We will advertise and conduct open meetings, Q&amp;A sessions and live webinars as the project progresses.

&nbsp;

We will circulate a regular email newsletter which gives the key outcomes of the project and progress against those indicators.

&nbsp;

We will share (in an open-format) a working document which will detail the ongoing evaluation dialogue. This will feature a learning lessons dialogue of ‘what went well’ and ‘even better if…’.

&nbsp;

A weekly video blog will capture the essential features of the project.

&nbsp;

‘Open’, anonymized registration documents showing the amount of take up for activities will be shared.

&nbsp;

Feature as part of information sessions held by Sheffield Digital.

&nbsp;

Presentations to local, regional and national professional audiences.

&nbsp;

Highlight work as part of ‘Future Dot Now’ coalition response.

column16:
We would very much look forward to establishing a strong working relationship with the designated Collaboration Manager.

&nbsp;

This would include representation to the differing departments within government who would have an interest in this work e.g. DCMS, DfE and BEIS amongst others.

&nbsp;

We would seek a commitment to a publication of project progress on the MHCLG website and supported social media platforms.

&nbsp;

Our experience of similar projects has shown the value of conversations and collaborations with other areas across the country – we would look to MCHLG to initiate, activate and successfully deliver these conversations and growing intellectual capital.

column17:
The Sheffield City Region (SCR) Local Economic Partnership (LEP) – already has a growing awareness of this area and is committed to supporting the Tech Sector. We would seek the LEP’s support in sharing the ambitions and progress of the project in their communication platforms.

&nbsp;

Local Government Association (LGA) – would act as a conduit to other authorities through their active dissemination networks.

&nbsp;

United Kingdom Tech Cluster Group (UKTCG) – Sheffield Digital is an established contributor to this forum so this network will be exploited for dissemination purposes.

&nbsp;

The Good Things Foundation – a national organisation based in Sheffield working on building digital skills.

column7:
The current stage for the research element is at inception, for the programme of activities it is at the proof of concept stage.

This project builds on earlier collaboration between the library service and the University of Oxford to research digital exclusion in Oxfordshire. This work has formed a strong base and methodology to assess the needs of digitally excluded communities.

&nbsp;

Furthermore, library staff have identified potential ways that libraries can draw together isolated older people by working in conjunction with health and wellbeing providers in Oxfordshire. Funding is needed; however, in order to deliver this programme and the challenges that COVID-19 has brought.

&nbsp;

This project will bring together these two strands to deliver lifechanging impacts on isolated individuals and develop a community of care to reduce the isolation that COVID-19 has caused.

&nbsp;

It also builds on initial planning with Sir Muir Gray from Optimal Ageing and Dr Anne Brice from Public Health England on the sustainability of health and wellbeing. This new paradigm requires action to promote physical cognitive and emotional resilience and fitness, strengthen social engagement and reducing isolation, digitally as well as face to face and strengthening the sense of purpose.

column10:
Success and impact will be demonstrated through a number of stages. Successful surveys and mapping of data of older populations in Oxfordshire who have been isolated as a result of COVID-19 will reveal areas for targeted response and understanding of the problems they have faced.

&nbsp;

We will regularly survey participants at activities and events, with an anticipated boost to mental health and the establishment of social contacts and networks.

&nbsp;

We will also measure success through our ability to increase developed collaboration with health and wellbeing providers in Oxfordshire.

column14:
This project will specifically focus on digitally excluded, and isolated segments of the population, focusing on older populations who have shielded during the period of COVID-19.

&nbsp;

Providing people in their 60s and beyond with a knowledge service and support service focused particularly on people who are housebound can reduce isolation, but this requires everyone over 60 to be online, identifying those without internet access, and a co-ordinated response across the community.

&nbsp;

We will ensure that the activities supporting them out of isolation will include both virtual and non-virtual participation so that those who are not able to visit libraries in person will not be excluded.

column16:
None

<span lang="EN"><span style="color: #000000;font-family: Arial">We acknowledge that each project must seek funding up to £80,000.00 and Wiltshire Council will fund any cost deficit to ensure the appropriate number of licenses are procured and the correct technical and project resources are made available to ensure that the project achieves the outputs detailed above. </span></span>

&nbsp;

column7:
Test project has delivered immediate IAG response for year 11, developed in partnership with schools, colleges and Southern Universities Network. Trial results indicate positive engagement delivered in April 2020 for Covid response. <a href="https://www.sunoutreach.org/resource-category/flying-start-portsmouth/">https://www.sunoutreach.org/resource-category/flying-start-portsmouth/</a>

&nbsp;

The current site links information and advice with opportunities for blended learning and self-study, particularly invaluable to year 11 learners who ceased full-time education in March 2020. Careers information, advice and guidance is delivered through the test site, with further support signposted for local Careers IAG.

&nbsp;

This project seeks to widen the project scope to those completing post-16 education, young unemployed and recent graduates. A broad service, pulling together local employment networks, statutory services, NCS delivery, working with skills delivery partners, business networks, Solent LEP and our local voluntary and community network, the proposed HUB is designed to provide a gateway site for young people, engaging those potentially affected by youth unemployment and linking them to support and opportunities for employment and education progression.

&nbsp;

The HUB will enable promotion of apprenticeship, traineeship and skills options, as well as targeted interventions using existing funded and new programmes with a "one stop shop" solution across the age groups. Adult signposting and partner information will be key to the success.

&nbsp;

The London Borough of Barking and Dagenham is one of four local authorities to work with the LGA to understand, identify and support the financially vulnerable. As a result, the Homes and Money (HAM) Hub (a physical set of support and consultation spaces in our libraries) was established in 2018 to assist residents with money and debt challenges. We’ve also participated in the BBC Radio 4 Fix radio series, highlighting the impact of debt on our residents.

&nbsp;

Existing website content signposts to other organisations because prior to covid research indicated that this is where people would seek financial support.

&nbsp;

However, since the pandemic, we’ve seen a +50% uplift in visits to our benefit, debt and money pages as residents turn towards us for support, indicating a major shift in behaviour and renewed responsibility for us as a local authority. Paired with the data we now have on the financially vulnerable residents supported during our BDCan coronavirus outreach, it’s clear we must improve our digital debt offer.

&nbsp;

We aim to create a scalable digital service blueprint with processes, resources, tools, information and guidance together under one umbrella - a digital HAM hub, allowing residents to self-diagnose/serve, providing immediate support and relief.

column13:
With 4.6m households amassing increasing debts as people fall behind on council tax, utilities and rent, many councils now face further service-cuts.

&nbsp;

With this project we aim to tackle a universal issue, with the “end product” being a live, reusable, digital service with scalable service patterns, processes and tools that any local authority will be able “lift, shift and implement” within their equivalent directorate. This will include structured content clusters, forms, digital tools as well as code sharing where possible.

&nbsp;

We will identify common themes, tools and needs, leveraging these from the outset. Where differing form providers or content management systems appear the process maps will bridge the gap, allowing a similar approach to be taken locally.

&nbsp;

We always strive to uphold the digital declaration and for this project, we are partnering with Greenwich and Lambeth to ensure that we develop solutions that will benefit as many residents as possible.

&nbsp;

column14:
We prioritize accessibility in the design of all content and services and regularly take action to improve our score. We have invested in a tool called SiteImprove to monitor indicators including accessibility, quality, readability, and SEO and as a result, all indicators currently rank at +90%.

&nbsp;

We regularly collaborate with the GDS empathy lab to ensure we design with users of varying permanent and temporary digital access challenges in mind, adhering to best practice guidance so that our services can be accessed effectively.

&nbsp;

Our discovery will involve residents of varying digital capabilities to enable digitally inclusive design with a mobile first ethos in mind, ensuring we comply with WCAG2 standards.

&nbsp;

Lastly, our digitisation isn’t designed to replace our physical support. Instead, we aim to improve the overall service by removing barriers for residents who wish to digitally self-serve thus releasing more resources for those presenting with the most complex needs.

column17:
We will collaborate with two other local authorities the Royal Borough of Greenwich &amp; London Borough of Lambeth to deliver this work at pace. To streamline delivery the LBBD digital and data teams will work on the discovery, prototyping and designs and we will share these blueprints, outputs, insight, analysis and tools as well as critique and shape the project priorities as a 3-way collective at the end of each week.

&nbsp;

We’ll also work with our local social sector to help us engage with the local community and shape a set of digital services and resources that our truly meaningful.

column14:
The technology requires a 3G/4G/5G-enabled smartphone running IOS or Android, but does not require access to broadband at home. Smartphone penetration in the UK is the highest in the world, with up to 90% of the population (and rising) having access. This gives confidence that we will reach those who are sometimes thought of as digitally excluded due to lack of access to a personal computer or a fast and reliable broadband connection.

&nbsp;

The technology specifically addresses ‘thin file’ residents who lack access to other types of identity or paper credential, by digitizing existing local trust networks, and allowing residents to collect reliable and re-useable credentials.

&nbsp;

The wallet itself, and the sharing of credentials are simple to use, requiring little in the way of digital skills. Furthermore, since transactions take place primarily peer-to-peer, we would envisage a high degree of skills transference when digital entitlements are being issued.

column10:
Success can be measured by the number of volunteers and organisations that are active in the new hub.

H&amp;F and some of the potential partner councils are already managing relationships with volunteers in various ways.  For H&amp;F this is largely done with spreadsheets and email exchanges.  Recording the volunteers, communications and feedback together in the hub will allow for Power BI dashboards to be built around activity.  These will provide transparent and auditable metrics on the impact of volunteer activity on the community.

&nbsp;

